	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;The Sisters&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;The Sisters.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.261410704198779</longitude>
			<latitude>53.35275899802055</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>105.5622881256366</heading>
			<tilt>45.13856745528481</tilt>
			<range>103.6345997808057</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Great Britain Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;The Sisters&quot;<br>[where the priest's sisters are caring for Father Flynn; where he dies]<br>&quot;The next morning after breakfast I went down to look at the little house in Great Britain Street. It was an unassuming shop, registered under the vague name of Drapery &quot; (11).<br><br>The name of the street was changed to Parnell Street after the death of Parnell. A history of the street&nbsp; is contained in <a href="http://issuu.com/scoyne73/docs/parnellstreeteast/1" target="_blank"><i><font size="2">Parnell Street: A Vision for an Historic City Centre Street</font></i><font size="2"><br></font></a></div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.260705,53.352909,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>St. Catherine&apos;s</name>
			<description>&quot;The Sisters&quot;
[where Father James Flynn served as priest]

&quot;Two poor women and a telegram boy were reading the card pinned on the crape. I also approached and read:

July 1st, 1895
The Rev. James Flynn (formerly of S. Catherine&apos;s Church, Meath Street), aged sixty-five years.
R.I.P.&quot; (12)</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.27840749030563</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34205095428231</latitude>
				<altitude>6.890662392146691</altitude>
				<heading>0.001311606648674516</heading>
				<tilt>33.35838679400212</tilt>
				<range>335.9340048697805</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>-6.27881924003777,53.3420099316512,24.02273494476195</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Irish College in Rome</name>
			<description>&quot;The Sisters&quot;
[where Father Flynn studied for the priesthood]
 
&quot;He had studied in the Irish college in Romeand he had taught me to pronounce Latin properly&quot; (13).</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>12.50205300007116</longitude>
				<latitude>41.8872900002544</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>4.747136889818372e-11</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>999.999992230869</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>12.50205300007116,41.8872900002544,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Persia</name>
			<description>&quot;The Sisters&quot;
[where the narrator imagines he might have been in his dream]

&quot;As I walked along in the sun I remembered Old Cotter&apos;s words and tried to remember what had happened afterwards in the dream. I remembered that I had noticed long velvet curtains and a swinging lamp of antique fashion. I felt that I had been very far away, in some land where the customs were strange--in Persia, I thought...But I could not remember the end of the dream&quot; (13-14).</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>53.68804181793316</longitude>
				<latitude>32.42790479830219</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-2.242582949018225e-06</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>1964888.856692486</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>53.68804181793316,32.42790479830219,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Irishtown</name>
			<open>1</open>
			<description><![CDATA["The Sisters"<br>[where Father Flynn and his sisters grew up]<br>"But still and all he kept on saying that before the summer was over 
he'd go out for a drive one fine day just to see the old house again 
where we were all born down in Irishtown and take me and Nannie with 
him. If we could only get one of them new-fangled carriages that makes 
no noise that Father O'Rourke told him about, them with the rheumatic 
wheels, for the day cheap -- he said, at Johnny Rush's over the way 
there and drive out the three of us together of a Sunday evening. He had
 his mind set on that.... Poor James!" (16)<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.223106555966232</longitude>
				<latitude>53.340992769622</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>2.917608175525065</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>3161.784892047926</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin5</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.219240822222928,53.33684709829025,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Johhny Rush&apos;s</name>
			<description>&quot;The Sisters&quot;
[where the sisters and Father Flynn had planned to get a carriage for a visit to Irishtown]
&quot;If we could only get one of them new-fangled carriages that makes no noise that Father O&apos;Rourke told him about—them with the rheumatic wheels—for the day cheap—he said, at Johnny Rush&apos;s over the way there and drive out the three of us together of a Sunday evening. He had his mind set on that.... Poor James!&quot; (17)</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.256698893156835</longitude>
				<latitude>53.35277874271539</latitude>
				<altitude>3.133245441460709</altitude>
				<heading>136.4853774397014</heading>
				<tilt>45.1378553474735</tilt>
				<range>100.6814560571561</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin12</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>-6.256698893156835,53.35277874271538,8.262309757574162</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;An Encounter&quot;</name>
		<description>Street, Locations, and Routes in &quot;An Encounter.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.251641732932618</longitude>
			<latitude>53.35601037503885</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>-1.296423119302893</heading>
			<tilt>37.10705927653709</tilt>
			<range>877.8516334937644</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Gardiner Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["An Encounter"<br>[where Joe Dillon's parents go to mass]<br><br>"His parents went to eight- o'clock mass every morning in Gardiner Street
 and the peaceful odour of Mrs. Dillon was prevalent in the hall of the 
house" (19).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.259119050349646</longitude>
				<latitude>53.35720488712262</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>6.49726338368487</heading>
				<tilt>41.71172426803538</tilt>
				<range>341.7815398337818</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin202</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.26022340636542,53.35784835872251,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Canal Bridge</name>
			<description><![CDATA["An Encounter"<br>[where the narrator meets Mahony]<br><br>"We were to meet at ten in the morning on the Canal Bridge" (21).<br><br>Two maps from 1836 and 1883 name this bridge Newcombe and Newcomen Bridge, respectively.]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.243805314155204</longitude>
				<latitude>53.35665440757322</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-1.909301949840659</heading>
				<tilt>24.26117634630861</tilt>
				<range>193.5224061499731</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin20</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.244153000000001,53.356522,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>North Strand Road</name>
			<description><![CDATA["An Encounter"<br>[After the Canal Bridge, the first street the narrator and his friend take on their journey]<br><br>"We walked along the North Strand Road till we came to the Vitriol Works and then turned to the right along the Wharf Road" (22).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.241705163693696</longitude>
				<latitude>53.3581968483197</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-3.696923426549979</heading>
				<tilt>33.13561159777353</tilt>
				<range>122.6799603787144</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin2020</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.241325,53.358517,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Wharf Road</name>
			<description><![CDATA["An Encounter"<br>[part of the boys' route]<br><br>"We walked along the North Strand Road till we came to the Vitriol Works and then turned to the right along the Wharf Road" (22).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.236970543097675</longitude>
				<latitude>53.35929252976211</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-11.3661444337516</heading>
				<tilt>45.0844012511515</tilt>
				<range>94.14163133347839</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin201</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.238606,53.36042800000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Ringsend</name>
			<description><![CDATA["An Encounter"<br>[the area past which the boats are that the boys watch; where the boys wander after crossing the Liffey]<br><br>"We pleased ourselves with the spectacle of Dublin's commerce -- the 
barges signalled from far away by their curls of woolly smoke, the brown
 fishing fleet beyond Ringsend, the big white sailing vessel which was 
being discharged on the opposite quay" (23).<br><br>"When we were tired of this sight we wandered slowly into Ringsend" (23).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.223419518922792</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34112503947026</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-8.699132503424405</heading>
				<tilt>22.91881941978069</tilt>
				<range>3398.905738261753</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin203</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.227366390125316,53.34275619544761,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>The Dodder</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;An Encounter&quot;<br>[the river that the boys can see from the sloping bank where they meet the josser]<br>&quot;We both felt rather tired and when we reached the field we made at once for a sloping bank over the ridge of which we could see the Dodder&quot; (24).</div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.228442207780897</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34038793145185</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.0001812546696368594</heading>
				<tilt>59.85685935485365</tilt>
				<range>305.3129351016642</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_ylw-pushpin2020</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.228218,53.340202,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
