				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>144.962982,-37.813187,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Melbourne, UK</name>
			<description><![CDATA[(alternatively)<br>"Eveline"<br>[where the priest in the photograph now lives]<br>"He had been a school friend of her father. Whenever he showed the 
photograph to a visitor her father used to pass it with a casual word:<br><br>-He is in Melbourne now" (37).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-1.414628219983195</longitude>
				<latitude>52.81882748569412</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.01101569831697432</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>6984.029465959624</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-1.428454,52.823006,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>The Stores</name>
			<description>&quot;Eveline&quot;
[where Eveline works]
&quot;Of course she had to work hard both in the house and at business. What would they say of her in the Stores when they found out that she had run away with a fellow?&quot; (37)</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.265326021075732</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34176433453035</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.0005732119382843461</heading>
				<tilt>31.18325761644828</tilt>
				<range>179.8880635023667</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_grn-pushpin</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.265572044458159,53.34135609739011,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Buenos Ayres</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Eveline&quot;<br>[where Frank wants to take Eveline]<br><br>&quot;She was to go away with him by the night-boat to be his wife and to live with him in Buenos Ayres where he had a home waiting for her&quot; (38).<br><br>&quot;He had fallen on his feet in Buenos Ayres, he said, and had come over to the old country just for a holiday&quot; (39).<br><br>&quot;If she went, tomorrow she would be on the sea with Frank, steaming towards Buenos Ayres&quot; (40).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-58.373161,-34.608418,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Canada</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Eveline"<br>[one of the places Frank travels on the <a href="http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/allan.html">Allan Line</a> (or the Montreal Ocean Steamship Company)]<br>"He had tales of distant countries. He had started as a deck boy at a 
pound a month on a ship of the Allan Line going out to Canada" (39).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-63.764648,44.684277,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Straits of Magellan</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Eveline"<br>[one of the areas Frank has explored in his travels]<br>"He told her the names of the ships he had been on and the names of the 
different services. He had sailed through the Straits of Magellan and he
 told her stories of the terrible Patagonians" (39).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-70.488281,-53.748711,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Patagonia</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Eveline"<br>[one of the areas Frank has explored in his travels]<br>"He told her the names of the ships he had been on and the names of the 
different services. He had sailed through the Straits of Magellan and he
 told her stories of the terrible Patagonians" (39).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-72.29003899999999,-52.038979,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Hill of Howth</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Eveline"<br>[where Eveline went as a child with her family when her mother was still alive]<br>"Another day, when their mother was alive, they had all gone for a picnic to the Hill of Howth" (39).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.07002,53.373192,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>North Wall</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Eveline"<br>[where Frank and Eveline go to catch the ship]<br>"She stood among the swaying crowd in the station at the North Wall" (40).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.243576880445115</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34787672316807</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.004527062444575459</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>1764.107776201585</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin20</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.245844078581435,53.3478145570936,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;After the Race&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets, Locations, and Routes in &quot;After the Race.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.335858999992482</longitude>
			<latitude>53.32862900029554</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>5.951612947688606e-12</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<range>1000.000264301766</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Naas Road</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br><div>[where the cars are at the beginning of the story]</div><div>"THE cars came scudding in towards Dublin, running evenly like pellets in the groove of the Naas Road" (42).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.335858999999999,53.328629,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Inchicore Square</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br><div>[the cars continue]</div><div>"At the crest of the hill at Inchicore sightseers had gathered in clumps 
to watch the cars careering homeward and through this channel of poverty
 and inaction the Continent sped its wealth and industry" (42).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.32167179650316,53.33957141830153,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>France</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[the country whose cars the Irish support; the country Segouin drives for; where Segouin is from and where he owns hotels; one of the places the men toast]<br><br>&quot;Now and again the clumps of people raised the cheer of the gratefully oppressed. Their sympathy, however, was for the blue cars -- the cars of their friends, the French.<br><br>The French, moreover, were virtual victors. Their team had finished solidly; they had been placed second and third and the driver of the winning German car was reported a Belgian. Each blue car, therefore, received a double measure of welcome as it topped the crest of the hill and each cheer of welcome was acknowledged with smiles and nods by those in the car. In one of these trimly built cars was a party of four young men whose spirits seemed to be at present well above the level of successful Gallicism: in fact, these four young men were almost hilarious&quot; (42).<br><br>&quot;Segouin was in good humour because he had unexpectedly received some orders in advance (he was about to start a motor establishment in Paris) and Riviere was in good humour because he was to be appointed manager of the establishment; these two young men (who were cousins) were also in good humour because of the success of the French cars&quot; (43).<br><br>&quot;They were not much more than acquaintances as yet but Jimmy found great pleasure in the society of one who had seen so much of the world and was reputed to own some of the biggest hotels in France&quot; (43).<br><br>&quot;The Frenchmen flung their laughter and light words over their shoulders and often Jimmy had to strain forward to catch the quick phrase&quot; (44).<br><br>&quot;At the control Segouin had presented him to one of the French competitors and, in answer to his confused murmur of compliment, the swarthy face of the driver had disclosed a line of shining white teeth. It was pleasant after that honour to return to the profane world of spectators amid nudges and significant looks&quot; (44).<br><br>&quot;Jimmy, whose imagination was kindling, conceived the lively youth of the Frenchmen twined elegantly upon the firm framework of the Englishman&#39;s manner&quot; (46).<br><br>&quot;Riviere, not wholly ingenuously, undertook to explain to Jimmy the triumph of the French mechanicians&quot; (46).<br><br>&quot;They drank Ireland, England, France, Hungary, the United States of America. Jimmy made a speech, a long speech, Villona saying: &quot;Hear! hear!&quot; whenever there was a pause&quot; (47).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>1.757813,47.39835000000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Germany</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where the car is from that is disqualified]<br>&quot;The French, moreover, were virtual victors. Their team had finished solidly; they had been placed second and third and the driver of the winning German car was reported a Belgian&quot; (42).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>9.667968999999999,50.289337,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Belgium</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where the driver of the disqualified German car is from]<br>&quot;The French, moreover, were virtual victors. Their team had finished solidly; they had been placed second and third and the driver of the winning German car was reported a Belgian&quot; (42).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>4.746094,51.124214,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Canada</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where Riviere was born]<br>&quot;They were Charles Segouin, the owner of the car; Andre Riviere, a young electrician of Canadian birth; a huge Hungarian named Villona and a neatly groomed young man named Doyle&quot; (42-43).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-69.609375,52.48277999999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Hungary</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where Villona is from; one of the places the men toast]<br><br>&quot;They were Charles Segouin, the owner of the car; Andre Riviere, a young electrician of Canadian birth; a huge Hungarian named Villona and a neatly groomed young man named Doyle&quot; (42-43).<br><br>&quot;The car ran on merrily with its cargo of hilarious youth. The two cousins sat on the front seat; Jimmy and his Hungarian friend sat behind&quot; (44).<br><br>&quot;His father, therefore, was unusually friendly with Villona and his manner expressed a real respect for foreign accomplishments; but this subtlety of his host was probably lost upon the Hungarian, who was beginning to have a sharp desire for his dinner&quot; (45-46).<br><br>&quot;The resonant voice of the Hungarian was about to prevail in ridicule of the spurious lutes of the romantic painters when Segouin shepherded his party into politics&quot; (46).<br><br>&quot;They drank Ireland, England, France, Hungary, the United States of America&quot; (47).<br><br>&quot;The cabin door opened and he saw the Hungarian standing in a shaft of grey light:<br><br>-Daybreak, gentlemen!&quot; (48).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>19.6875,46.98025100000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Kingstown</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br>[where Jimmy's father had started his business]<br>"His father, who had begun life as an advanced Nationalist, had modified 
his views early. He had made his money as a butcher in Kingstown and by 
opening shops in Dublin and in the suburbs he had made his money many 
times over" (43).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.142570184161525,53.28852901087195,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dublin University</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where Jimmy Doyle went to study law]<br>&quot;He had sent his son to England to be educated in a big Catholic college and had afterwards sent him to Dublin University to study law. Jimmy did not study very earnestly and took to bad courses for a while&quot; (43).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.258795,53.344471,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Cambridge</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where Jimmy goes to college for a term &quot;to see a little life&quot;]<br>&quot;Then he had been sent for a term to Cambridge to see a little life. His father, remonstrative, but covertly proud of the excess, had paid his bills and brought him home. It was at Cambridge that he had met Segouin&quot; (43).<br><br>&quot;The party was increased by a young Englishman named Routh whom Jimmy had seen with Segouin at Cambridge&quot; (46).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>0.116613,52.205303,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dame Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br><div>[the drive continues]</div><div>"They drove down Dame Street. The street was busy with unusual traffic, 
loud with the horns of motorists and the gongs of impatient 
tram-drivers. Near the Bank Segouin drew up and Jimmy and his friend 
alighted" (45).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.26478,53.344173,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Grafton Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br><div>[where the car goes after Jimmy and Villona get out; later where they meet Farley, the American]</div><div><br>&nbsp;</div><div>"The car steered out slowly for Grafton Street while the two young men pushed their way through the knot of gazers" (45).</div><div><br>&nbsp;</div><div>"At the corner of Grafton Street a short fat man was putting two handsome
 ladies on a car in charge of another fat man. The car drove off and the
 short fat man caught sight of the party" (47)</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259439,53.342903,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Stephen&apos;s Green</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where the men walk, smoking, after dinner]<br>&quot;The five young men strolled along Stephen&#39;s Green in a faint cloud of aromatic smoke&quot; (46).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.260629,53.339832,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>United States of America</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;After the Race&quot;<br>[where Farley is from; a place the men toast]<br><br>&quot;Farley was an American&quot; (47).<br><br>&quot;They got into a rowboat at the slip and made out for the American&#39;s yacht&quot; (47).<br><br>&quot;They drank Ireland, England, France, Hungary, the United States of America&quot; (47).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-88.242188,37.996162,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Westland Row</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br>[where the men get the train to go to the harbour]<br>"They took the train at Westland Row and in a few seconds, as it seemed to Jimmy, they were walking out of Kingstown Station" (47).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.249869,53.343182,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Kingstown Harbour</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br>[where the men deboard the train and board Farley's yacht]<br>"They took the train at Westland Row and in a few seconds, as it seemed 
to Jimmy, they were walking out of Kingstown Station...It
 was a serene summer night; the harbour lay like a darkened mirror at 
their feet...They
 got into a rowboat at the slip and made out for the American's yacht. 
There was to be supper, music, cards" (47).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.135135,53.29718400000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>&quot;After the Race&quot; Car Route</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br>[the route the car takes as it drives into town]<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin10</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					-6.329744445912101,53.33226351369493,0 -6.328618769164685,53.33401373706663,0 -6.327692899486061,53.33494994602501,0 -6.321386815325354,53.33925763904858,0 -6.320316560006854,53.34048602426518,0 -6.319847940215233,53.34102983746226,0 -6.318849814364482,53.34159901713272,0 -6.313754030929616,53.34231442285525,0 -6.307899531055864,53.34199497310967,0 -6.307700750252167,53.34061193943158,0 -6.303820046134683,53.34074215054507,0 -6.301472491064885,53.34101364286575,0 -6.295398116324041,53.34196595462173,0 -6.289731470277792,53.3434318212137,0 -6.285030049105571,53.34349679892438,0 -6.281488052080641,53.34322199933695,0 -6.277463568196144,53.34283063278264,0 -6.275207208838848,53.34338644138064,0 -6.272027115543483,53.34289179974493,0 -6.271523710812762,53.34292534334358,0 -6.270655872994024,53.34315930657442,0 -6.270375819197441,53.34325954564822,0 -6.269906055383863,53.34321068991321,0 -6.268958600894918,53.34336607436711,0 -6.26771916332669,53.34367347401533,0 -6.267574006900531,53.34377449000712,0 -6.267636555002318,53.34406983943033,0 -6.267075505967147,53.34414998426293,0 -6.266233118965334,53.34416512715137,0 -6.264456393920036,53.3441684184241,0 -6.262382173589062,53.34423305015976,0 -6.262330149912214,53.34410553603127,0 -6.262241210816917,53.34395511636843,0 -6.261719743901828,53.34357742922366,0 -6.260842202975313,53.34386736823242,0 -6.260288940190547,53.34363229547743,0 -6.259639202866744,53.34335690767841,0 -6.259448654432113,53.34328885980528,0 -6.259357389185233,53.34324799918732,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>&quot;After the Race&quot; Walking/Car/Train Route</name>
			<description><![CDATA["After the Race"<br>[the route the men take after dinner and on their way to the yacht]<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin4</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					-6.256072,53.338703,0 -6.260911,53.339966,0 -6.260846,53.34008799999999,0 -6.253413,53.337975,0 -6.250151000000001,53.34189600000001,0 -6.250581000000001,53.342049,0 -6.249624,53.343586,0 -6.246464,53.342823,0 -6.243177472379315,53.34190369334807,0 -6.240702441621932,53.34093951523606,0 -6.234892267387688,53.33818998461552,0 -6.233463357763325,53.33731930545484,0 -6.22798417272879,53.33321336010279,0 -6.213341980912523,53.3220394408422,0 -6.210348016887184,53.31994832832839,0 -6.198903025070896,53.31235550765514,0 -6.192637270092404,53.3085600884095,0 -6.179316483306694,53.30312638251376,0 -6.176180630301689,53.30204999148898,0 -6.173842400312379,53.30135183616575,0 -6.171791964582004,53.30089804440823,0 -6.168729413240428,53.30013325477285,0 -6.166008154091069,53.29936056887176,0 -6.16239560539916,53.29818267896363,0 -6.156913076953428,53.29614188222724,0 -6.155301735518945,53.29577517059068,0 -6.153530272937822,53.29547059065775,0 -6.150903851706573,53.29540442283552,0 -6.148574596658673,53.29558402825324,0 -6.145785485035264,53.29589371297917,0 -6.141581088883874,53.29630200481554,0 -6.139857057413809,53.29626925737784,0 -6.138099299124146,53.29608955339313,0 -6.136779148609801,53.29582831809902,0 -6.135700357040326,53.29550999637425,0 -6.135198079058469,53.29527080240592,0 -6.134352612212446,53.29492859530398,0 
				</coordinates>
