		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;Two Gallants&quot;</name>
		<description><![CDATA[Streets, Locations, and Routes in "Two Gallants."<br><br>End route according to Gifford.]]></description>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Rutland Square</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where the story starts; where Lenehan returns as he walks alone]<br><br>&quot;Two young men came down the hill of Rutland Square. On of them was just bringing a long monologue to a close. The other, who walked on the verge of the path and was at times obliged to step on to the road, owing to his companion&#39;s rudeness, wore an amused listening face&quot; (49).<br><br>&quot;He turned to the left when he came to the corner of Rutland Square and felt more at ease in the dark quiet street, the sombre look of which suited his mood&quot; (56-57).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.262904,53.352695,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dorset Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan has been talking all day before walking with Corley]<br>&quot;His tongue was tired for he had been talking all the afternoon in a public-house in Dorset Street&quot; (50).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.265104000000001,53.356174,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dame Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<br>[where Corley picked up his girl]<br>"--One night, man, he said, I was going along Dame Street and I spotted a
 fine tart under Waterhouse's clock and said good- night, you know. So 
we went for a walk round by the canal and she told me she was a slavey 
in a house in Baggot Street" (50).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.263527,53.344185,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Baggot Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<br>[where Corley's girl is a "slavey"; where Lenehan sees the couple later]<br>"--One night, man, he said, I was going along Dame Street and I spotted a
 fine tart under Waterhouse's clock and said good- night, you know. So 
we went for a walk round by the canal and she told me she was a slavey 
in a house in Baggot Street" (50).<br><br>"They turned down Baggot Street and he followed them at once, taking the other footpath" (59).]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.253025,53.33799,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Donnybrook</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Corley takes his girl one day; possibly where the two are going when they break off from Lenehan]<br><br>&quot;I put my arm round her and squeezed her a bit that night. Then next Sunday, man, I met her by appointment. We vent out to Donnybrook and I brought her into a field there&quot; (50-51).<br><br>&quot;He kept the pair in view until he had seen them climbing the stairs of the Donnybrook tram; then he turned about and went back the way he had come&quot; (56).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.23594,53.32170099999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Pim&apos;s</name>
			<description>&quot;Two Gallants&quot;
[where Corley claims to have worked]

&quot;--Maybe she thinks you&apos;ll marry her, said Lenehan.

--I told her I was out of a job, said Corley. i told her I was in Pim&apos;s. She doesn&apos;t know my name. i was too hairy to tell her that. But she thinks I&apos;m a bit of class, you know&quot; (51).</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.265888537635575</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34127507264372</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.001024464349621534</heading>
				<tilt>31.18324698990775</tilt>
				<range>177.6031439573132</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin12</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<gx:drawOrder>1</gx:drawOrder>
				<coordinates>-6.265551083841626,53.34140295425303,14.55381216941777</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>South Circular</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<br>[one place where Corley used to pick up girls]<br>""First I used to go with girls, you know," said Corley, unbosoming; "girls off the South Circular" (52).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.293612,53.335018,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Earl Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<br>[where Corley saw one of his girls in a car]<br>"-She's on the turf now. I saw her driving down Earl Street one night with two fellows with her on a car" (53).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259001845281045,53.35007563674542,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Trinity College Dublin</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Corley and Lenehan are toward the beginning of the story]<br><br>&quot;As they passed along the railings of Trinity College, Lenehan skipped out into the road and peered up at the clock&quot; (53).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.258795,53.344471,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Nassau Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<div>[where the men walk, talking about women]</div><div><br>&nbsp;</div><div>"<span style="font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif">They walked along Nassau Street and then turned into Kildare Street. Not far from the porch of the club a harpist stood in the roadway, playing to a little ring of listeners" (54).</span></div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.256338,53.342583,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Kildare Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where the men encounter the harpist]<br><br>&quot;They walked along Nassau Street and then turned into Kildare Street. Not far from the porch of the club a harpist stood in the roadway, playing to a little ring of listeners&quot; (54).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.254697,53.34186600000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Stephen&apos;s Green</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan and Corley cross the street; where Lenehan continues to walk once he is alone; the direction of which Corley walks to meet back up with Lenehan]<br><br>&quot;When they reached Stephen&#39;s Green they crossed the road. Here the noise of trams, the lights and the crowd released them from their silence&quot; (54).<br><br>&quot;He walked listlessly round Stephen&#39;s Green and then down Grafton Street&quot; (56).<br><br>&quot;He set off briskly along the northern side of the Green hurrying for fear Corley should return too soon&quot; (59).<br><br>&quot;The door closed on her and Corley began to walk swiftly towards Stephen&#39;s Green&quot; (60).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.2568,53.338818,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Hume Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Two Gallants"<br>[the corner near Stephen's Green where Lenehan and Corley spot Corley's girl standing; the street Lenehan walks down to get a closer look]<br><br>"At the corner of Hume Street a young woman was standing. She wore a blue
 dress and a white sailor hat. She stood on the curbstone, swinging a 
sunshade in one hand" (54).<br><br>"Lenehan observed them for a few minutes. Then he walked rapidly along 
beside the chains at some distance and crossed the road obliquely. As he
 approached Hume Street corner he found the air heavily scented and his 
eyes made a swift anxious scrutiny of the young woman's appearance" (55).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.254324,53.337605,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Merrion Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Corley and Lenehan are going to meet; where Lenehan follows the couple; where Lenehan awaits their return]<br><br>--And after? Where will we meet?<br><br>--Half ten, answered Corley, bringing over his other leg.<br><br>--Where?<br><br>--Corner of Merrion Street. We&#39;ll be coming back.&quot; (55)<br><br>&quot;After waiting for a little time he saw them coming towards him and, when they turned to the right, he followed them, stepping lightly in his white shoes, down one side of Merrion Square&quot; (56).<br><br>&quot;When he reached the corner of Merrion Street he took his stand in the shadow of a lamp and brought out one of the cigarettes which he had reserved and lit it. He leaned against the lamp-post and kept his gaze fixed on the part from which he expected to see Corley and the young woman return&quot; (59).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.253634999999999,53.33814599999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>The Shelbourne Hotel</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan stops and waits to see Corley and the girl before he begins following them]<br>&quot;Lenehan walked as far as the Shelbourne Hotel where he halted and waited&quot; (56)</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.256564,53.338818,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Duke&apos;s Lawn</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan first finds himself alone]<br>&quot;His gaiety seemed to forsake him and, as he came by the railings of the Duke&#39;s Lawn, he allowed his hand to run along them&quot; (56).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.252036,53.340122,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Grafton Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[one of the streets Lenehan walks after leaving Corley and returns to after eating]<br><br>&quot;He walked listlessly round Stephen&#39;s Green and then down Grafton Street&quot; (56).<br><br>&quot;He turned to the left at the City Markets and walked on into Grafton Street&quot; (58).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259223999999999,53.343891,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Capel Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan walks after finishing his meal]<br>&quot;He paid twopence halfpenny to the slatternly girl and went out of the shop to begin his wandering again. He went into Capel Street and walked along towards the City Hall&quot; (58).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.267979,53.346146,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>City Hall</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[one of the landmarks along Lenehan&#39;s wandering path]<br>&quot;He paid twopence halfpenny to the slatternly girl and went out of the shop to begin his wandering again. He went into Capel Street and walked along towards the City Hall&quot; (58)</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.26725,53.344082,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dame Street and George&apos;s Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Two Gallants&quot;<br>[where Lenehan meets his friends]<br>&quot;Then he turned into Dame Street. At the corner of George&#39;s Street he met two friends of his and stopped to converse with them&quot; (58).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin8</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.264471,53.344154,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>City Markets</name>
			<description>&quot;Two Gallants&quot;
[where Lenehan turns off of George&apos;s Street as he makes his way back to meet Corley]
&quot;He turned to the left at the City Markets and walked onto Grafton Street&quot; (58).</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-6.264415409926557</longitude>
				<latitude>53.34270570787157</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>8.783085237755243e-05</heading>
				<tilt>36.48933149614134</tilt>
				<range>285.7987121165464</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
