	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;The Boarding House&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;The Boarding House.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.263493998992336</longitude>
			<latitude>53.35648000063955</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>8.085057465534e-10</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<range>1019.158129777168</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Spring Gardens</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;The Boarding House&quot;<br>[the place near where Mrs. Mooney first opens the butcher shop with Mr. Mooney]<br>&quot;She had married her father&#39;s foreman and opened a butcher&#39;s shop near Spring Gardens&quot; (61).<br><br>(found with Gilbert, John Thomas. A History of the City of Dublin, Vol. 2. Dublin: McGlashan and Gill, 1859, pp. 280.)</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin1</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.2421143804085,53.35965657525689,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Hardwicke Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;The Boarding House&quot;<br>[where the boarding house is located]<br>&quot;Mrs. Mooney, who had taken what remained of her money out of the butcher business and set up a boarding house in Hardwicke Street, was a big imposing woman&quot; (62).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.263494,53.35647999999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Liverpool</name>
			<description><![CDATA["The Boarding House"<br>[where some of the tourists come from]<br>"Her house had a floating population made up of tourists from Liverpool 
and the Isle of Man and, occasionally, artistes from the music halls" (62).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-2.977838,53.410778,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Isle of Man</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">United Kingdom<br>&quot;The Boarding House&quot;<br>[where some of the the tourists are from]<br>&quot;Her house had a floating population made up of tourists from Liverpool and the Isle of Man and, occasionally, artistes from the music halls&quot; (62).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-4.561996,54.23868199999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Fleet Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["The Boarding House"<br>[where Jack Mooney works]<br>"Jack Mooney, the Madam's son, who was clerk to a commission agent in Fleet Street, had the reputation of being a hard case" (62).]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259802000000001,53.345814,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Saint George&apos;s</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;The Boarding House&quot;<br>[a church close to the boarding house]<br>&quot;The belfry of George&#39;s Church sent out constant peals and worshippers, singly or in groups, traversed the little circus before the church, revealing their purpose by their self-contained demeanour no less than by the little volumes in their gloved hands&quot; (63).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.262851,53.357273,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Marlborough Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["The Boarding House"<br>[where Mrs. Mooney plans to "catch short twelve"]<br>"It was seventeen minutes past eleven: she would have lots of time to 
have the matter out with Mr. Doran and then catch short twelve at 
Marlborough Street" (64).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin6</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.258446999999999,53.350693,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;A Little Cloud&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets, Locations, and Routes in &quot;A Little Cloud.&quot;</description>
		<Style>
			<ListStyle>
				<listItemType>check</listItemType>
				<bgColor>00ffffff</bgColor>
				<maxSnippetLines>2</maxSnippetLines>
			</ListStyle>
		</Style>
		<Placemark>
			<name>North Wall</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>[where Chandler saw Gallaher off]<br>"EIGHT years before he had seen his friend off at the North Wall and wished him godspeed" (70).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin11</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.245342200070115,53.34782649196635,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>London</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>[where Gallaher lives, working for The London Press; where Gallaher suggests Chandler go]<br><br>"Little Chandler's thoughts ever since lunch-time had been of his meeting
 with Gallaher, of Gallaher's invitation and of the great city London 
where Gallaher lived" (70).<br><br>"The friend whom he had known under a shabby and necessitous guise had become a brilliant figure on the London Press" (71).<br><br>"Ignatius Gallaher on the London Press! Who would have thought it possible eight years before?" (72)<br><br>"Perhaps Gallaher might be able to get it into some London paper for him" (73).<br><br>"Every step brought him nearer to London, farther from his own sober inartistic life" (73).<br><br>"--But Hogan has a good sit, hasn't he?<br><br>--Yes; he's in the Land Commission.<br><br>--I met him one night in London and he seemed to be very flush.... Poor O'Hara! Boose, I suppose?" (75-76)<br><br>"--Go to London or Paris: Paris, for choice. That'd do you good" (76).<br><br>
"There was something vulgar in his
 friend which he had not observed before. But perhaps it was only the 
result of living in London amid the bustle and competition of the Press.
 The old personal charm was still there under this new gaudy manner" (77).<br><br>"--Then it is an immoral city, said Little Chandler, with timid insistence -- I mean, compared with London or Dublin?" (77)<br><br>"--London! said Ignatius Gallaher. It's six of one and half-a-dozen of 
the other. You ask Hogan, my boy. I showed him a bit about London when 
he was over there. He'd open your eye.... I say, Tommy, don't make punch
 of that whisky: liquor up" (77).<br><br>"Was it too late for him to try to live bravely like Gallaher? Could he go to London?" (83)<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-0.2271030674759422</longitude>
				<latitude>51.50131732786858</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.0789402032582447</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>238674.5461891159</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-0.126236,51.500153,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Henrietta Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>[where Chandler emerges from his office]<br>"He emerged from under the feudal arch of the King's Inns, a neat modest figure, and walked swiftly down Henrietta Street" (71).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.270396,53.352585,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Corless&apos;s</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>[where Chandler meets Gallaher]<br><br>"He had never been in Corless's but he knew the value of the name. He 
knew that people went there after the theatre to eat oysters and drink 
liqueurs; and he had heard that the waiters there spoke French and 
German. Walking swiftly by at night he had seen cabs drawn up before the
 door and richly dressed ladies, escorted by cavaliers, alight and enter
 quickly. They wore noisy dresses and many wraps. Their faces were 
powdered and they caught up their dresses, when they touched earth, like
 alarmed Atalantas. He had always passed without turning his head to 
look" (72).<br><br>"He pursued his revery so ardently that he passed his street and had to 
turn back. As he came near Corless's his former agitation began to 
overmaster him and he halted before the door in indecision" (74).<br><br>(based on Gifford, Don. Joyce Annotated: Notes for Dubliners and A Portrait of the Artist As a Young Man, 2nd ed.Berkeley: U of California P, 1982 , pp. 68)<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.261048,53.34384900000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Capel Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Little Cloud&quot;<br>[the direction towards which Chandler turns; and the street he walks down]<br><br>&quot;He turned to the right towards Capel Street&quot; (72).<br><br>&quot;Little Chandler quickened his pace. For the first time in his life he felt himself superior to the people he passed. For the first time his soul revolted against the dull inelegance of Capel Street&quot; (73).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.269867,53.35076100000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Grattan Bridge</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Little Cloud&quot;<br>[the bridge Chandler crosses on his way to meet Gallaher]<br><br>&quot;As he crossed Grattan Bridge he looked down the river towards the lower quays and pitied the poor stunted houses. They seemed to him a band of tramps, huddled together along the riverbanks, their old coats covered with dust and soot, stupefied by the panorama of sunset and waiting for the first chill of night bid them arise, shake themselves and begone&quot; (73).<br><br>&quot;There were so many things he wanted to describe: his sensation of a few hours before on Grattan Bridge, for example&quot; (84).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.267743000000001,53.345608,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Isle of Man</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Little Cloud&quot;<br>[somewhere Chandler has been]<br>--Have you never been anywhere even for a trip?<br><br>--I&#39;ve been to the Isle of Man, said Little Chandler.<br><br>Ignatius Gallaher laughed.<br><br>--The Isle of Man! he said. Go to London or Paris: Paris, for choice. That&#39;d do you good&quot; (76).<br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-4.369508083130054</longitude>
				<latitude>54.01393637600914</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.1559753894580582</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>325237.4614181627</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-4.561996,54.23868199999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Paris</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>
[where Gallaher suggests Chandler go]<br>
"--Go to London or Paris: Paris, for choice. That'd do you good. <br>
--Have you seen Paris?" (76)<br>
<br>
"--It's not so beautiful, you know. Of course, it is beautiful.... But 
it's the life of Paris; that's the thing. Ah, there's no city like Paris
 for gaiety, movement, excitement...." (76)<br><br>"--Everything in Paris is gay, said Ignatius Gallaher. They believe in 
enjoying life -- and don't you think they're right? If you want to enjoy
 yourself properly you must go to Paris. And, mind you, they've a great 
feeling for the Irish there" (77).<br><br>"--Tell me, he said, is it true that Paris is so... immoral as they say?<br><br>Ignatius Gallaher made a catholic gesture with his right arm.<br><br>--Every place is immoral, he said. Of course you do find spicy bits in Paris. Go to one of the students' balls, for instance" (77).<br><br>"There's no woman like the Parisienne -- for style, for go" (77).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>2.327397157483757</longitude>
				<latitude>48.88454937178169</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>-0.01776870816614176</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>44431.09604763232</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>2.350987,48.856667,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Moulin Rouge</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Little Cloud&quot;<br>[a place Gallaher has been]<br><br>&quot;--I&#39;ve been to the Moulin Rouge, Ignatius Gallaher continued when the barman had removed their glasses, and I&#39;ve been to all the Bohemian cafes. Hot stuff! Not for a pious chap like you, Tommy&quot; (76).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin110</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>2.33247,48.88412100000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Berlin</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Little Cloud"<br>[a place Gallaher likes]<br>"He summarised the vices of many capitals and seemed inclined to award the palm to Berlin" (78).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>13.44247036643581</longitude>
				<latitude>52.51722262659827</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.02465648335756365</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>25226.58844423441</range>
