	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;A Painful Case&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;A Painful Case.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.268606874019864</longitude>
			<latitude>53.3438658482069</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>-5.673432309413866</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<range>5483.331879315573</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Chapelizod</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case" <br>[where Mr. Duffy lives]<br>"MR. JAMES DUFFY lived in Chapelizod because he wished to live as far as 
possible from the city of which he was a citizen and because he found 
all the other suburbs of Dublin mean, modern and pretentious. He lived 
in an old sombre house and from his windows he could look into the 
disused distillery or upwards along the shallow river on which Dublin is
 built" (107).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.342888,53.347271,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Baggot Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Duffy works]<br>"He had been for many years cashier of a private bank in Baggot Street" (108).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.252487,53.337933,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dan Burke&apos;s</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Duffy eats lunch]<br>"At midday he went to Dan Burke's and took his lunch -- a bottle of lager beer and a small trayful of arrowroot biscuits" (108).<br>(according to Gifford)<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.248155,53.33629999999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>George&apos;s Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Painful Case&quot;<br>[where Duffy eats dinner]<br>&quot;He dined in an eating-house in George&#39;s Street where he felt himself safe from the society o Dublin&#39;s gilded youth and where there was a certain plain honesty in the bill of fare&quot; (108-09).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.264439,53.34306,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Rotunda</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Painful Case&quot;<br>[where Duffy meets Mrs. Sinico]<br>&quot;One evening he found himself sitting beside two ladies in the Rotunda&quot; (109).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.262035,53.352692,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Earlsfort Terrace</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Duffy meets Mrs. Sinico for a second time]<br>"He met her again a few weeks afterwards at a concert in Earlsfort 
Terrace and seized the moments when her daughter's attention was 
diverted to become intimate" (110).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.257424,53.33450299999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Leghorn</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Mr. Sinico is from]<br>"Her name was Mrs. Sinico. Her husband's great-great-grandfather had come from Leghorn" (110).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>12.13919699684127</longitude>
				<latitude>43.43197411606796</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>1.259440176428177</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>548504.4156967021</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>10.308011,43.551876,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Holland</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Mr. Sinico sails on his mercantile ship]<br>"Her husband was captain of a mercantile boat plying between Dublin and Holland; and they had one child" (110).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>4.960091769112389</longitude>
				<latitude>52.19135453618983</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.3081382229272982</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>189118.8079828619</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>4.570313,52.281601,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Parkgate</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where the cakeshop is that Duffy and Mrs. Sinico meet for the last time]<br>"As he did not wish their last interview to be troubled by the influence 
of their ruined confessional they meet in a little cakeshop near the 
Parkgate" (112).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.301602999999999,53.349476,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>City of Dublin Hospital</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[the hospital where Mrs. Sinico is taken]<br>"Today at the City of Dublin Hospital the Deputy Coroner (in the absence 
of Mr. Leverett) held an inquest on the body of Mrs. Emily Sinico, aged 
forty-three years, who was killed at Sydney Parade Station yesterday 
evening" (113).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.244239,53.333538,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Sydney Parade Station</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Painful Case&quot;<br>[where Mrs. Sinico is hit by the train]<br>&quot;Today at the City of Dublin Hospital the Deputy Coroner (in the absence of Mr. Leverett) held an inquest on the body of Mrs. Emily Sinico, aged forty-three years, who was killed at Sydney Parade Station yesterday evening&quot; (113).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.211846,53.32094599999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Rotterdam</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Mr. Sinico is when he gets news of his wife's death]<br>"He stated that the deceased was his wife. He was not in Dublin at the 
time of the accident as he had arrived only that morning from Rotterdam" (114).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>4.481776,51.924217,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Lucan Road</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[the view from Duffy's window as he reads the newspaper story]<br>"The river lay quiet beside the empty distillery and from time to time a light appeared in some house on the Lucan road" (115).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.352844,53.351372,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Chapelizod Bridge?</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[a place Duffy passes as he walks]<br>"When he came to the public-house at Chapelizod Bridge he went in and ordered a hot punch" (116).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.293793,53.348087,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>County Kildare</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[the county the estate is in that the men are talking about]<br>"There were five or six workingmen in the shop discussing the value of a gentleman's estate in County Kildare" (116).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.908998,53.159828,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Magazine Hill</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Duffy sits]<br>"When he gained the crest of the Magazine Hill he halted and looked along
 the river towards Dublin, the lights of which burned redly and 
hospitably in the cold night" (117).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.309242,53.349422,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Kingsbridge Station</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Painful Case"<br>[where Duffy watches and hears the train]<br>"Beyond the river he saw a goods train winding out of Kingsbridge 
Station, like a worm with a fiery head winding through the darkness, 
obstinately and laboriously. It passed slowly out of sight; but still he
 heard in his ears the laborious drone of the engine reiterating the 
syllables of her name" (117).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.294823,53.346554,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;Ivy Day in the Committee Room&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;Ivy Day in the Committee Room.&quot;</description>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Wicklow Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Ivy Day in the Committee Room"<br>[where the Committee Room is]<br>"Mr. O'Connor had been engaged by Tierney's agent to canvass one part of<br>the ward but, as the weather was inclement and his boots let in the wet,<br>he spent a great part of the day sitting by the fire in the Committee<br>Room in Wicklow Street with Jack, the old caretaker" (119).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.260875,53.34293399999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Christian Brothers School</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Ivy Day in the Committee Room&quot;<br>[where old Jack sent his son to school]<br>&quot;--Ah, yes, he said, continuing, it&#39;s hard to know what way to bring up children. Now who&#39;d think he&#39;d turn out like that! I sent him to<br>the Christian Brothers and I done what I could him, and there he goes boosing about. I tried to make him someway decent&quot; (119).<br></div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.250766999999999,53.35815,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Aungier Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Ivy Day in the Committee Room"<br>[where O'Connor has been canvassing]<br><br>"--Did you serve Aungier Street? he asked Mr. O'Connor.<br><br>--Yes, said Mr. O'Connor, beginning to search his pockets for memoranda" (122).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.26579,53.339985,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Mary&apos;s Lane</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Ivy Day in the Committee Room"<br>[where Richard Tierney's father had a shop]<br><br>"--O, he's as tricky as they make 'em, said Mr. Henchy. He hasn't got those little pigs' eyes for nothing. Blast his soul! Couldn't he pay up like a man instead of: 'O, now, Mr. Henchy, I must speak to Mr. Fanning.... I've spent a lot of money'? Mean little schoolboy of hell! I suppose he forgets the time his little old father kept the hand-me-down shop in Mary's Lane.<br><br>--But is that a fact? asked Mr. O'Connor.<br><br>--God, yes, said Mr. Henchy. Did you never hear that? And the men used to go in on Sunday morning before the houses were open to buy a waistcoat or a trousers--moya! But Tricky Dicky's little old father always had a tricky little black bottle up in a corner. Do you mind now? That's that. That's where he first saw the light" (123).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.272536,53.348087,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Suffolk Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Ivy Day in the Committee Room"<br>[where O'Connor saw Cowley and two others]<br>"--There's some deal on in that quarter, said Mr. O'Connor thoughtfully. I saw the three of them hard at it yesterday at Suffolk Street corner" (127).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.260443,53.34365099999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dawson Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Ivy Day in the Committee Room"<br>[where Henchy has been canvassing]<br>"--Yes. I got him one or two sure things in Dawson Street, Crofton and<br>myself" (129).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin9</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.258230000000001,53.341309,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;A Mother&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;A Mother.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.25314652382462</longitude>
			<latitude>53.34436471839782</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>-2.437073340895622</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<range>4326.715322974999</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Ormond Quay</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[where Mr Kearney works as a bootmaker]<br>"However, when she drew near the limit and her friends began to loosen their tongues about her, she silenced them by marrying Mr. Kearney, who was a bootmaker on Ormond Quay" (137).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.269793999999999,53.345806,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Skerries</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[one of the places the Kearney's vacation]<br>"Every year in the month of July Mrs. Kearney found occasion to say to some friend:<br><br>--My good man is packing us off to Skerries for a few weeks.<br><br>If it was not Skerries it was Howth or Greystones" (137).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.106991,53.580788,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Howth</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>
[one of the places the Kearney's vacation]<br>
"Every year in the month of July Mrs. Kearney found occasion to say to some friend:<br>
<br>
--My good man is packing us off to Skerries for a few weeks.<br>
<br>
If it was not Skerries it was Howth or Greystones" (137).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.068042,53.386848,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Greystones</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>
[one of the places the Kearney's vacation]<br>
"Every year in the month of July Mrs. Kearney found occasion to say to some friend:<br>
<br>
--My good man is packing us off to Skerries for a few weeks.<br>
<br>
If it was not Skerries it was Howth or Greystones" (137).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.075536,53.13911400000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Cathedral Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[the street whose corner the Kearneys and their friends gather occasionally]<br>"On special Sundays, when Mr. Kearney went with his family to the pro-cathedral, a little crowd of people would assemble after mass at the corner of Cathedral Street" (137).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.25935,53.350548,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Antient Concert Rooms</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[where the concert series takes place]<br><br>"Therefore she was not surprised when one day Mr. Holohan came to her and proposed that her daughter should be the accompanist at a series of four grand concerts which his Society was going to give in the Antient Concert Rooms" (138).<br><br>"When Mrs. Kearney arrived with her daughter at the Antient Concert Rooms<br>on Wednesday night she did not like the look of things" (139).<br><br>"Mrs. Kearney, with her husband and<br>daughter, arrived at the Antient Concert Rooms three-quarters of an hour before the time at which the concert was to begin" (141).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.250387,53.34446,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Brown Thomas&apos;s</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[where Mrs Kearney buys the chermeuse]<br>"Everything went on smoothly. Mrs. Kearney bought some lovely blush-pink<br>charmeuse in Brown Thomas's to let into the front of Kathleen's dress" (138).<br><br>(According to Gifford the shop is located somewhere in Grafton Street.)<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259718,53.34282699999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>London</name>
			<description><![CDATA["A Mother"<br>[where Madam Glynn is from]<br>"Mr. Holohan said that she was Madam Glynn from London" (143).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-0.09606962782409578</longitude>
				<latitude>51.50828848343491</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.02371022654324636</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>14760.22972043098</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-0.126364,51.50016000000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Mansion House</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;A Mother&quot;<br>[where the American priest is speaking]<br><br>&quot;The Freeman man had come in to say that he could not wait for the concert as he had to report the lecture which an American priest was giving in the Mansion House&quot; (144).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#m_ylw-pushpin100</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.250387,53.341236,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>&quot;Grace&quot;</name>
		<description>Streets and Locations in &quot;Grace.&quot;</description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>-6.234764181896605</longitude>
			<latitude>53.36137485405369</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>-0.7890086565671015</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<range>11708.72927945813</range>
			<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Grafton Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Grace&quot;<br>[where the bar is]<br>&quot;When they came out into Grafton Street, Mr. Power whistled for an outsider&quot; (153).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.260147,53.341751,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Westmoreland Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace" <br>[the direction the car drives]<br>"The car drove off towards Westmoreland Street" (153).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.259073999999999,53.346001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Crowe Street</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace"<br>[where Kernan's office is]<br>"Modern business methods had spared him only so far as to allow him a little office in Crowe Street, on the window blind of which was written the name of his firm with the address--London, E. C." (154)<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.263783,53.34456299999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Dublin Castle</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Grace&quot;<br>[where Mr Power works]<br>&quot;Mr. Power, a much younger man, was employed in the Royal Irish Constabulary Office in Dublin Castle&quot; (154).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.266194,53.34308999999999,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>The Glasnevin road</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace"<br>[where Kernan lives]<br>"The car halted before a small house on the Glasnevin road and Mr. Kernan was helped into the house" (154).<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.272317137951521,53.36358855513777,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Fogarty&apos;s</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace"<br>[where Mrs Kernan offers to go to get something for Mr power]<br>"--I'm so sorry, she continued, that I've nothing in the house to offer you. But if you wait a minute I'll send round to Fogarty's, at the corner" (155).<br>(Gifford notes that this location is a possibility [102].)<br>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.265431,53.361523,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Star of the Sea Church</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div dir="ltr">&quot;Grace&quot;<br>[where the Kernans were married]<br>&quot;In her days of courtship, Mr. Kernan had seemed to her a not ungallant figure: and she still hurried to the chapel door whenever a wedding was reported and, seeing the bridal pair, recalled with vivid pleasure how she had passed out of the Star of the Sea Church in Sandymount, leaning on the arm of a jovial well-fed man, who was dressed smartly in a frock-coat and lavender trousers and carried a silk hat gracefully balanced upon his other arm&quot; (156).</div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-6.219973,53.33575100000001,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Glasgow</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace"<br>[where one of the Kernans' sons lives]<br>"Her two eldest sons were launched. One was in a draper's shop in Glasgow and the other was clerk to a tea-merchant in Belfast" (156).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-4.243444567444296</longitude>
				<latitude>55.86645764126894</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.012950155540949</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>6447.464224053281</range>
				<gx:altitudeMode>relativeToSeaFloor</gx:altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#sn_blue-pushpin0</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-4.25909,55.865536,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>Belfast</name>
			<description><![CDATA["Grace"<br>[where one of the Kernans' sons lives]<br>"Her two eldest sons were launched. One was in a draper's shop in Glasgow and the other was clerk to a tea-merchant in Belfast" (156).<br>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-5.788501762343233</longitude>
				<latitude>54.60174169828085</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0.1154270733511629</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<range>29057.61393661406</range>
